arly six hundred women occupy posts from municipal offices, school boards, and county offices to seats in the Texas House and Senate. In this book, five Latina political scientists profile the women who have been the first Latinas to hold key elected and appointed positions in Texas government. Through interviews with each woman or her associates, the authors explore and theorize about Latina officeholders' political socialization, decision to run for office and obstacles overcome, leadership style, and representational roles and advocacy. The profiles begin with Irma Rangel, the first Latina elected to the Texas House of Representatives, and Judith Zaffirini and Leticia Van de Putte, the only two Latinas to serve in the Texas Senate. The authors also interview Lena Guerrero, the first and only Latina to serve in a statewide office; judges Linda Yanes, Alma Lopez, Elma Salinas Ender, Mary Roman, and Alicia Chacón; mayors Blanca Sanchez Vela (Brownsville), Betty Flores (Laredo), and Olivia Serna (Crystal City); and Latina city councilwomen from San Antonio, El Paso, Dallas, Houston, and Laredo.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aMexican American women politicianszTexas. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / General.2bisacsh1 aCoronado, Irasema, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aJaramillo, Patricia A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aMadrid, Patricia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMartinez-Ebers, Valerie, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Texas Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311074534440uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/71729940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292794597423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/97802927945